---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { CONTACT_EMAIL } from '../consts';

const title = 'About Questling — Why we built it';
const description =
  'Questling started with a simple question: what if a kid\'s phone handed them an adventure instead of another video? Here\'s the story.';
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <span class="section__eyebrow">About</span>
      <h1>We think kids deserve a better default than a screen.</h1>

      <p class="lead">
        Questling started with a small, stubborn question: <em>what if the phone in
        the house handed a kid an adventure instead of another video?</em>
      </p>

      <p>
        Like a lot of families, we watched "go play" quietly turn into "go watch."
        Not because anyone was doing anything wrong — screens are just the easiest
        thing in the room, designed by very smart people to stay that way. We didn't
        want to fight that with guilt or lectures. We wanted to fight it with
        something more fun.
      </p>

      <p>
        So we built Questling around a simple loop: a parent picks a real-world
        quest, checks it with their kid, they do it together, and the kid earns gems
        to trade for rewards the parent chooses — and you can save photos of it all to
        a memory journal. Outdoor and creative challenges — build a fort, find a stick
        shaped like a sword, draw the backyard — small enough to start today, real
        enough to feel like something.
      </p>

      <p>
        Two beliefs are baked into every part of it:
      </p>

      <blockquote>
        Parents stay in control. And the outdoors should feel exciting again — not
        like a chore a kid is being forced into.
      </blockquote>

      <p>
        That's why nothing happens without a parent's tap, and why every quest is
        built to spark curiosity rather than nag. Questling isn't anti-screen. It's
        pro-everything-else.
      </p>

      <p>
        We're a small team building this carefully, in the open, one piece at a time.
        Questling is <strong>coming soon to the App Store</strong> — and if you want a
        nudge the day it lands, <a href="/#get-notified">leave your email</a> or just
        <a href={`mailto:${CONTACT_EMAIL}`}>say hello</a>. We read everything.
      </p>

      <a class="btn btn--gem" href="/#get-notified">Get notified at launch</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .container--narrow { max-width: 720px; }
  h1 { margin-top: 0.6rem; }
  .lead { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--ink); margin: 1rem 0 1.4rem; }
  p { font-size: 1.06rem; color: var(--ink); }
  blockquote {
    margin: 1.6rem 0; padding: 0.8rem 1.4rem; border-left: 4px solid var(--gem);
    background: var(--gem-tint); border-radius: 0 12px 12px 0; font-style: italic; font-size: 1.1rem;
  }
  .btn { margin-top: 1.4rem; }
</style>
